I"Z<h1 id="sequence-kernel-association-test">Sequence kernel association test</h1>
<h2 id="data-notation">Data Notation</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Assume \(n\) subjects are sequenced in a region with \(p\) variant sites observed.</li>
  <li>Covariates might include age, gender, and top principal components of genetic variation to control population stratification.</li>
  <li>For the \(i\)-th subject:
    <ul>
      <li>\(y_i\) denotes the phenotype variable,</li>
      <li>\(X_i = (X_{i1}, X_{i2}, \ldots, X_{im})\) represents the covariates,</li>
      <li>\(G_i = (G_{i1}, G_{i2}, \ldots, G_{ip})\) indicates the genotypes for the \(p\) variants within the region.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>An additive genetic model is typically assumed where \(G_{ij} = 0, 1, \text{ or } 2\) denotes the number of copies of the minor allele. Dominant and recessive models can also be considered.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="example">Example</h3>

<p>Consider sequencing 200 subjects with 10 variant sites in a specific genomic region, having three covariates: age, gender, and the first principal component of genetic variation (PC1).</p>

