<h2 id="linear-skat-model-and-test">Linear SKAT Model and Test</h2>

<p>To analyze this data, we might consider both linear and logistic models. For continuous traits, we use the linear model described by:</p>

\[y_i = \alpha_0 + \alpha'X_i + \beta'G_i + \epsilon_i\]

<p>Where:</p>
<ul>
  <li>\(\alpha_0\) is the intercept,</li>
  <li>\(\alpha\) is the vector of regression coefficients for the covariates,</li>
  <li>\(\beta\) is the vector of regression coefficients for the genetic variants.</li>
</ul>

<p>For dichotomous traits, such as blood pressure categorized as high or normal, we use the logistic model:</p>

\[\text{logit} P(y_i = 1) = \alpha_0 + \alpha'X_i + \beta'G_i\]

<p>Where \(P(y_i = 1)\) represents the probability of the \(i\)-th subject having high blood pressure.</p>

<h3 id="skat-analysis">SKAT Analysis</h3>

<p>SKAT enhances the power of the tests by assuming each \(\beta_j\) follows an arbitrary distribution with mean zero and variance \(w_j\tau\), where \(\tau\) is a variance component and \(w_j\) is a pre-specified weight for variant \(j\).</p>

<p>Given a matrix \(G\) of genotypes and a diagonal matrix \(W\) of weights, we compute the kernel matrix \(K\) as follows:</p>

\[K = GWG'\]

<p>Where \(K(G_i, G_j) = \sum_{k=1}^{p} w_k G_{ik} G_{jk}\) measures the genetic similarity between subjects based on their genotypes adjusted by variant weights. This framework allows for a robust examination of the influences of multiple genetic variants on diseases such as high blood pressure.</p>

<p>This model provides a robust method for testing the effect of genetic variants on phenotypes while controlling for important covariates and is particularly effective in analyzing genetic data where the effect of any single variant may be small but the collective effect of multiple variants could be substantial.</p>

